Hashtable in Java

Hashtable is a class in Java that stores data as key → value pairs, similar to HashMap.

👉 Но это старый (legacy) класс, который использовался до появления HashMap.

Key Features
thread-safe ✅ (synchronized)
does NOT allow null keys ❌
does NOT allow null values ❌
slower than HashMap
part of legacy Java (older design)
Creating a Hashtable
import java.util.Hashtable;

Hashtable<String, Integer> table = new Hashtable<>();
Common Methods
put()
table.put("Apple", 10);
table.put("Banana", 20);
get()
table.get("Apple");
remove()
table.remove("Banana");
containsKey() / containsValue()
table.containsKey("Apple");
table.containsValue(10);
Thread Safety

👉 Hashtable is fully synchronized

This means:

every method is locked
only one thread can access it at a time

👉 Result:

safe ✅
but slow ❌
Null Handling
table.put(null, 10);   // ❌ throws exception
table.put("A", null);  // ❌ throws exception
Hashtable vs HashMap
Feature	Hashtable	HashMap
Thread-safe	✅	❌
Performance	Slower	Faster
Null key/value	❌	✅
Modern usage	Rare	Very common
Hashtable vs ConcurrentHashMap
Feature	Hashtable	ConcurrentHashMap
Locking	Full lock	Fine-grained
Performance	Slow	Fast
Modern	❌	✅
When to use Hashtable

👉 Almost never in modern Java

Use instead:

HashMap → for single-threaded
ConcurrentHashMap → for multi-threaded
Summary
Hashtable is a legacy thread-safe map
uses full synchronization (slow)
does not allow null keys/values
mostly replaced by HashMap and ConcurrentHashMap
